{"key":"post-8879738","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>8879738</id>\n<content>Actually, humidity doesn't 'fall'.&amp;nbsp; My greenhouses are always higher humidity on the upper shelves than on the lower ones.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;A cool mist works by shooting a fine mist straight up into the air.&amp;nbsp; For this reason, the humidifier should be on the floor of the greenhouse, with nothing above.&amp;nbsp; If the mist hits a shelf above, the stream will condense and drip back down, making a mess on the floor.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;I'd put the cool mist on the floor of one side of your greenhouse, making sure the mist(you can see it) goes straight up without hitting walls or shelves.&amp;nbsp; This will not only give the most humidity, but it will circulate the air inside the greenhouse.&amp;nbsp; If you'll cut windows and slits in the plastic, the circulating air will cause fresh air to be drawn in through the openings.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>8880117</next>\n<prev>8879438</prev>\n<first>8879267</first>\n<last>8882403</last>\n<when>1220587762</when>\n<utime>09/05/08 07:09 AM</utime>\n</post>"}